            "\n\nNarrated Abdullah, narrated to me Abu Abdul Rahman Abdullah bin Umar, narrated to us Abu Muawiyah, from Abdul Rahman bin Ishaq al-Qurashi, from Siyar Abu al-Hakam, from Abu Wa'il:\n\nA man came to Ali, may Allah be pleased with him,\nand said: O Commander of the Faithful, I have failed in my writing (contract) so help me.\n\nAli, may Allah be pleased with him, said: Shall I not teach you words that the Messenger of Allah ﷺ taught me? If you had a debt as large as Mount Sair of gold, Allah would pay it off for you?\n\nI said: Yes.\n\nHe said: Say: O Allah, suffice me with what is lawful against what is unlawful,\nand enrich me by Your bounty from needing anyone besides You.\nNarrated by Tirmidhi\n",
            "\n\nFatima came to the Messenger of Allah ﷺ asking him for a servant,\n\nand he said to her: Say:\n\nO Allah, Lord of the seven heavens and Lord of the Great Throne, our Lord and the Lord of everything, the Revealer of the Torah, the Gospel, and the Criterion, the Splitter of the grain and the date-stone, I seek refuge in You from the evil of everything You have taken by the forelock. You are the First, so there is nothing before You, and You are the Last, so there is nothing after You, and You are the Apparent, so there is nothing above You, and You are the Hidden, so there is nothing beyond You. Relieve us of debt and enrich us from poverty.\n\nNarrated by Muslim\n",
            "\n\nO Allah, Lord of the seven heavens and Lord of the earth, and Lord of the Great Throne, our Lord and the Lord of everything, the Splitter of the grain and the date-stone, the Revealer of the Torah, the Gospel, and the Criterion, I seek refuge in You from the evil of everything You have taken by the forelock. O Allah, You are the First, so there is nothing before You, and You are the Last, so there is nothing after You, and You are the Apparent, so there is nothing above You, and You are the Hidden, so there is nothing beyond You. Relieve us of debt and enrich us from poverty.\n",
            "\n\nThe Prophet ﷺ missed Mu'adh on Friday, and when he prayed, the Messenger of Allah ﷺ came to Mu'adh and said: O Mu'adh, why did I not see you? He said: O Messenger of Allah, I have a debt to a Jew who has a weight of gold and I went out to you, but he held me back. The Messenger of Allah ﷺ said to him: O Mu'adh, shall I not teach you a supplication that you can say and if you had a debt like Mount Sair, Allah would pay it off for you? And Sair is a mountain in Yemen. So Mu'adh called upon Allah saying: O Allah, Owner of the Kingdom, You give the kingdom to whom You will and take the kingdom from whom You will, You honor whom You will and humble whom You will. In Your hand is [all] good. Indeed, You are over all things competent. You cause the night to enter the day, and You cause the day to enter the night, You bring the living out of the dead, and You bring the dead out of the living, and You give provision to whom You will without account. The Most Merciful of this world and the Hereafter and their Most Compassionate, You give from them whom You will and withhold from them whom You will. Have mercy on me with a mercy that will enrich me from the mercy of anyone other than You.\n",
