          'FarajAdkartxtShow': [
            "\n\nThe Messenger of Allah ﷺ used to say during distress:\n\nThere is no god but Allah, the Great, the Forbearing.\nThere is no god but Allah, Lord of the Great Throne.\nThere is no god but Allah, Lord of the heavens and Lord of the earth and Lord of the Noble Throne.\n\nNarrated by Bukhari and Muslim.\n",
            "\n\nIn Sahih Bukhari and Sahih Muslim, the Prophet ﷺ said:\nOur Lord, Blessed and Exalted, descends every night to the lowest heaven when the last third of the night remains, and says:\n\nWho is calling upon Me, so I may answer him?\nWho is asking Me, so I may give him?\nWho is seeking My forgiveness, so I may forgive him?\n",
            "\n\nThe Prophet ﷺ said:\nWhoever consistently seeks forgiveness,\nAllah will make a way out for him from every tight situation,\nand will relieve him from every worry,\nand will provide for him from where he does not expect.\n\nNarrated by Abu Dawood, an-Nasa'i, and Ibn Majah.\n",
            "\n\nOn the authority of Ubayy ibn Ka'b,\n\nI said: O Messenger of Allah,\n\nI send blessings upon you frequently, how much of my supplications should I devote to you?\n\nHe said: As much as you wish.\n\nI said: A quarter?\n\nHe said: As much as you wish, but if you increase it, it is better for you.\n\nI said: Half?\n\nHe said: As much as you wish, but if you increase it, it is better for you.\n\nI said: Two-thirds?\n\nHe said: As much as you wish, but if you increase it, it is better for you.\n\nI said: Shall I devote all my supplications to you?\n\nHe said: Then you will be freed from your worries, and your sins will be forgiven.\n\nNarrated by Tirmidhi and Hakim in Al-Mustadrak.\n",
            "\n\nIn Sunan Abu Dawood and Sunan Ibn Majah,\n\nfrom the narration of Asma' bint Umays, she said:\n\nThe Messenger of Allah ﷺ said to me:\n\nShall I not teach you words to say during distress or in times of hardship?\n\nAllah, Allah is my Lord, I do not associate anything with Him.\n",
            "\n\nNarrated by Ahmad and others from Ibn Mas'ud, may Allah be pleased with him, who said:\n\nThe Messenger of Allah ﷺ said:\n\nNo one has ever been afflicted with anxiety or sorrow, and then says:\n\nO Allah, I am Your servant,\nson of Your servant,\nson of Your maidservant.\nMy forelock is in Your hand.\nYour command over me is forever executed\nand Your decree over me is just.\nI ask You by every name belonging to You\nwhich You have named Yourself with,\nor revealed in Your Book,\nor taught to any of Your creation,\nor have preserved in the knowledge of the unseen with You,\nthat You make the Quran the life of my heart\nand the light of my chest,\nand a departure for my sorrow and a release for my anxiety.\n\nBut Allah will take away his anxiety and sorrow, and replace it with relief.\n\nIt was said: O Messenger of Allah, should we not learn it?\nHe said: Yes, whoever hears it should learn it.\n",
            "\n\nNarrated by Ahmad and Abu Dawood from Nafi' ibn Harith that the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said:\n\nThe supplications of the distressed are:\n\nO Allah, I hope for Your mercy.\nDo not leave me to myself even for the blink of an eye.\nRectify all of my affairs for me.\nThere is no god but You.\n",
            "\n\nNarrated by Bukhari and Muslim from Ibn Abbas, may Allah be pleased with them, who said:\n\nThe Prophet ﷺ used to supplicate during distress, saying:\n\nThere is no god but Allah, the Great, the Forbearing.\nThere is no god but Allah, Lord of the heavens and Lord of the earth\nand Lord of the Great Throne.\n",
            "\n\nOn the authority of Anas bin Malik, may Allah be pleased with him, who said:\n\nI was sitting with the Messenger of Allah ﷺ,\nand a man was standing and praying.\nWhen he bowed and prostrated, he recited the Tashahhud and supplicated:\n\nO Allah, I ask You because all praise is due to You.\nThere is no god but You, the Bestower,\nCreator of the heavens and the earth,\nO Possessor of majesty and honor,\nO Ever-Living, O Sustainer, I ask You.\n\nThe Prophet ﷺ said to his companions:\nDo you know what he has supplicated with?\nThey said: Allah and His Messenger know best.\n\nHe said: By Him in Whose hand is my soul, he has supplicated to Allah by His Greatest Name,\nwhich, if He is called upon by it, He responds,\nand if asked by it, He gives.\n\nNarrated by an-Nasa'i and Imam Ahmad.\n",
            "\n\nThe Prophet ﷺ said:\n\nO Allah, I seek refuge in You from anxiety and sorrow,\nI seek refuge in You from weakness and laziness,\nI seek refuge in You from cowardice and miserliness,\nand I seek refuge in You from the burden of debts and the oppression of men.\n\nNarrated by Bukhari and others.\n",
            "\n\nOn the authority of Anas who said:\n\nThe Messenger of Allah ﷺ said to Mu'adh:\n\nShall I not teach you a supplication that you can say?\nEven if you have a debt as large as Mount Uhud, Allah will pay it off for you.\n\nSay, O Mu'adh:\n\nO Allah, Owner of the kingdom,\nYou give the kingdom to whom You will.\nIn Your hand is all good. Indeed,\nYou are over all things competent.\nMost Merciful of this world and the Hereafter and their Most Compassionate.\nYou give them to whom You will,\nand withhold from them whom You will.\nHave mercy on me with a mercy that will enrich me from the mercy of anyone other than You.\n\nNarrated by At-Tabarani in Al-Kabir with a good chain of narration,\nand authenticated by Al-Albani.\n",
            "\n\nO Allah, suffice me with what is lawful against what is unlawful, and enrich me by Your bounty from needing anyone besides You.\n"
